04685nam a22006495i 9781487584702DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191966onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875847027 a10.3138/97814875847022doi  a(DE-B1597)527916  a(OCoLC)1129181911  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPR2976b.S658 2018 7aLIT0150002bisacsh04a822.332231 aBodwell Smith, Marion, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDualities in Shakespeare /cMarion Bodwell Smith. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1966  a1 online resource (260 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tI. The Humanist Synthesis -- tII. Two Distincts, Division None: The Nature of Shakespeare's Dualities -- tIII. The Poetry of Ambivalence -- tIV. The War of the Elements: Imagery in Romeo and Juliet -- tV. Twelfth Night in Twelfth Night -- tVI. The Laws of Ethical Polity and the Meanings of "Measure" -- tVII. The Poisoned Chalice: Dualism in Macbeth -- tVIII. No Midway: The Structure of Duality in Antony and Cleopatra -- tIX. Mockery and Cherished Purpose: Duality of Intention in The Tempest -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is a study of particular aspects of particular works in a particular context. The context, in general terms, is the humanist search for a synthesis or order based on the reconciliation of oppositions, for unity in difference, in spite of growing philosophical disillusionment and social disruption. More and more successfully -- in artistic terms at least -- than his fellow-dramatists. Shakespeare was able to achieve such reconciliations by utilizing opposed forces as the ingredients of both dramatic and poetic tension and by resolving conflicts between them on the basis of inclusion rather than exclusion. For Shakespeare, there is always "a soul of goodness in things evil" and a dram of evil in the best; in all human experience, as in Friar Laurence's flower, "poison hath residence, and medicine power." In exploiting the dramatic possibilities of the essential dualities of human existence, all the aspects of Shakespeare's art become increasingly involved. The book opens with a discussion of the contemporary climate of opinion in regard to the paradoxes of the human condition and the development of Shakespeare's attitudes towards them as demonstrated in his plays. Here, the emphasis is on dualities as thematic material. Subsequent chapters discuss the ways in which concepts of duality operate in paticular works, focussing, in each instance, on a particular aspect of Shakespeare's art -- the treatment of love in the Sonnets, the imagery of Romeo and Juliet, the inversions of Twelfth Night and Macbeth, the levels of order and justice in Measure for Measure, the structure of Antony and Cleopatra, and duality of intention in The Tempest. Well written, sensitive, and lively, this work will appeal to "the great variety of Readers" who joyfully accept the invitation of Shakespeare's first editors to "Reade him . againe, and againe."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148758470240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487584702423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487584702.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles